WEBVTT

00:00.469 --> 00:03.769
Please, don't try anything
you're about to see at home.

00:03.794 --> 00:06.094
We're what you call "experts."

00:09.119 --> 00:11.219
On this episode of MythBusters...

00:11.244 --> 00:12.544
- Dear MythBusters...
- Dear MythBusters...

00:12.568 --> 00:13.369
Dear MythBusters...

00:13.394 --> 00:15.594
...it's the Mailbag Special...

00:15.619 --> 00:16.819
To the bomb range.

00:16.844 --> 00:20.744
...as Tory, Grant and Kari
answer your questions...

00:20.769 --> 00:21.969
- That is correct!
- Whoo!

00:21.994 --> 00:24.394
...criticisms, and concerns.

00:24.419 --> 00:26.719
You asked, we're delivering.

00:26.744 --> 00:29.644
Your mini-myths are tackled and tested.

00:29.669 --> 00:31.569
Just remember, aim for the melons.

00:31.594 --> 00:34.494
There are exclusive
behind the scenes... scenes...

00:34.519 --> 00:35.419
Hello.

00:35.444 --> 00:38.744
...and in world firsts,
unseen footage is unearthed.

00:38.769 --> 00:41.369
These are hot.

00:41.394 --> 00:45.694
So, strap in for a wild ride,
because you are in charge.

00:46.219 --> 00:47.119
In three...

00:47.144 --> 00:47.844
two...

00:47.869 --> 00:48.769
one...

00:48.994 --> 00:50.894
- Whoo!
- Whooooooo!

00:53.819 --> 00:56.219
Who are the MythBusters?

00:56.669 --> 00:57.769
Adam Savage...

00:57.771 --> 00:59.371
It's scientific!

00:59.373 --> 01:01.206
and Jamie Hyneman.

01:01.208 --> 01:03.441
Jamie wants big boom.

01:03.443 --> 01:07.879
Between them, more than 30 years
of special-effects experience.

01:07.881 --> 01:09.514
Together with Kari Byron...

01:09.516 --> 01:11.916
Science gets more fun
when I get a bigger gun.

01:11.918 --> 01:14.386
- Tory Belleci...
- We survived!

01:14.388 --> 01:15.887
and Grant Imahara.

01:15.889 --> 01:17.088
Start the car!

01:17.090 --> 01:19.557
They don't just tell the myths.

01:19.559 --> 01:22.127
They put them to the test.

01:22.129 --> 01:26.529
MythBusters 10x09 - Mailbag Special
Original air date May 20, 2012

01:26.554 --> 01:30.954
Sync and corrections by atrn97g
for www.addic7ed.com

01:30.970 --> 01:32.971
Okay, so we're not in the blueprint room,

01:32.973 --> 01:35.740
and we are surrounded...
I mean surrounded... by mail.

01:35.742 --> 01:38.443
This is the Kari/Tory/Grant
Mailbag Special,

01:38.445 --> 01:39.744
and this is the mail.

01:43.483 --> 01:45.683
I come from the planet Butt Head.

01:45.685 --> 01:47.185
But we've also gone through

01:47.187 --> 01:50.522
and found all the concerns,
questions, myths, criticisms

01:50.524 --> 01:51.856
from all of our fans.

01:51.858 --> 01:53.725
And we're gonna open up as many as we can

01:53.727 --> 01:55.326
and answer them as best as we can.

01:56.696 --> 01:58.963
Give it a spin.

01:58.965 --> 02:00.965
Mythbuster history is littered with letters

02:00.967 --> 02:04.169
suggesting stories and revisit ideas.

02:04.171 --> 02:05.370
All right.

02:05.372 --> 02:07.138
Pick one.

02:07.140 --> 02:08.973
And the mailbag here at H.Q.

02:08.975 --> 02:10.675
fills as fast as we can empty it.

02:10.676 --> 02:12.343
Yeah, my inbox is stuffed.

02:12.345 --> 02:14.412
But this time, the team will tackle

02:14.414 --> 02:16.981
every letter's suggestion,
not just the myths,

02:16.983 --> 02:19.517
which means they're in your hands.

02:19.519 --> 02:21.653
And things are about to get crazy.

02:21.655 --> 02:23.488
You know what? I found a letter.

02:23.490 --> 02:25.490
"Adam and Jamie said,
'better to end with a bang.'"

02:28.094 --> 02:30.628
"Can you <i>start</i> with a bang?"

02:30.630 --> 02:32.297
"Can you blow up an office cubicle?"

02:32.299 --> 02:34.766
- I like it!
- To the bomb range.

02:36.502 --> 02:38.536
Okay.

02:38.538 --> 02:40.538
So, the first out-of-left-field letter

02:40.540 --> 02:42.140
is to assemble

02:42.142 --> 02:45.677
and then, with explosives,
disassemble an office cubicle.

02:45.679 --> 02:49.047
In a parallel universe
in the early '90s...

02:50.450 --> 02:52.851
this is where I'd be...
accounts receivable.

02:52.853 --> 02:54.519
Can we start
with a bang, you ask?

02:54.521 --> 02:57.055
Well, the answer is, "yes. Yes, we can."

02:57.057 --> 02:59.090
And the man in charge of the charge

02:59.092 --> 03:01.259
is honorary mythbuster Frank Doyle.

03:01.261 --> 03:06.431
We have taken a M112 block of C-4,

03:06.433 --> 03:08.399
which is about one pound,

03:08.401 --> 03:10.668
and then we will be command-detonating it

03:10.670 --> 03:11.836
from a distance away.

03:13.472 --> 03:15.773
With the blast shield in place,

03:15.775 --> 03:17.308
it's all systems "blow."

03:17.310 --> 03:18.443
All right.

03:18.445 --> 03:19.644
So, this is the viewer request

03:19.646 --> 03:21.012
"is it better to start with a bang?"

03:21.014 --> 03:23.882
In 3...2...1...

03:23.884 --> 03:25.984
Fire.

03:25.986 --> 03:27.285
Whoo!

03:31.590 --> 03:33.458
Well, that confirms it.

03:33.460 --> 03:35.627
A quick bang is the perfect hors d'oeuvre

03:35.629 --> 03:37.095
for the mailbag main course

03:37.097 --> 03:39.230
definitely good to start with a bang.

03:39.232 --> 03:41.132
Hopefully the next letter
actually has a myth in it.

03:41.134 --> 03:43.434
- Oh, I don't mind.
- I know.

03:43.436 --> 03:46.838
All right. Next letter.

03:46.840 --> 03:49.240
"Dear MythBusters, is it really true"

03:49.242 --> 03:52.443
"that it's impossible to eat
a spoonful of cinnamon"

03:52.445 --> 03:54.012
"without drinking water?"

03:54.014 --> 03:55.847
Okay, I am <i>not</i> into this one.

03:55.849 --> 03:57.815
I mean, cinnamon is not only an irritant,

03:57.817 --> 03:59.684
but it's also hydrophilic.

03:59.686 --> 04:01.419
It absorbs water like crazy.

04:01.421 --> 04:03.955
So, consequently, wouldn't it be
virtually impossible

04:03.957 --> 04:05.757
to eat a spoonful without drinking?

04:05.759 --> 04:07.659
Well, there's only one way to find out.

04:07.661 --> 04:09.928
Let's set up on the shop floor
and give it a try.

04:11.231 --> 04:13.298
It's a dangerous
Internet phenomenon.

04:13.300 --> 04:16.100
To spoon a mouthful of cinnamon
without water

04:16.101 --> 04:19.103
is supposedly impossible
and definitely painful.

04:19.105 --> 04:21.706
It's already sent scores
of people to the hospital.

04:21.708 --> 04:26.377
So, with a medic standing by,
the team gets set to swallow.

04:26.379 --> 04:28.580
Now, maybe you're thinking,
"spoonful of cinnamon?"

04:28.582 --> 04:30.481
"What's so dangerous about that?"

04:30.483 --> 04:32.217
Well, because it's hydrophilic,

04:32.219 --> 04:34.786
it dries up your saliva instantly,

04:34.788 --> 04:36.788
which can cause coughing and vomiting.

04:36.790 --> 04:38.690
Plus, if you accidentally inhale it,

04:38.692 --> 04:40.592
it can cause breathing difficulties,

04:40.594 --> 04:42.727
throat irritation, and even pneumonia.

04:44.096 --> 04:45.697
Kari's first up.

04:45.699 --> 04:47.732
I've never seen you hesitate so...

04:52.204 --> 04:53.504
Aah! Not on me!

04:53.506 --> 04:54.973
Holy crap!

04:54.975 --> 04:56.407
You want some water?

04:59.078 --> 05:00.211
Is sh...

05:00.213 --> 05:01.579
You okay?

05:01.581 --> 05:03.615
Yeah. That was great.

05:03.617 --> 05:05.850
Not only could Kari not swallow,

05:05.852 --> 05:07.819
but her near-choking fit illustrates

05:07.821 --> 05:09.354
that this is <i>not</i> child's play.

05:09.356 --> 05:11.322
For a second there,
I couldn't breathe.

05:11.324 --> 05:12.690
In fact...

05:12.692 --> 05:16.094
You know the uvula
that causes the gag reflex?

05:16.096 --> 05:19.063
It's actually cinnamon-coated right now.

05:22.302 --> 05:24.369
I shouldn't be laughing this hard,

05:24.371 --> 05:25.737
but, man, that's funny.

05:25.739 --> 05:27.939
Oh, laugh now, Tory.

05:27.941 --> 05:29.307
Your turn will come.

05:29.309 --> 05:30.508
But first, it's Grant...

05:30.510 --> 05:31.743
Seriously?

05:31.745 --> 05:33.144
who's taking a moment

05:33.146 --> 05:36.447
to steel his famously
not-so-steely stomach.

05:39.718 --> 05:41.152
Okay. Ready?

05:41.154 --> 05:43.021
I'll be so impressed if you can do this.

05:43.023 --> 05:44.088
Yeah, you can.

05:44.090 --> 05:45.823
Look at that.

05:47.026 --> 05:49.761
Kind of meditating and, like,
trying to put saliva into it.

05:49.763 --> 05:51.963
No, I think he's trying to
go to the bathroom.

05:55.402 --> 05:56.734
Oh, man, did I look like that?

05:56.736 --> 05:57.902
No.

05:57.904 --> 05:59.370
Oh, God.

05:59.372 --> 06:01.172
I think he's going to his unhappy place.

06:05.178 --> 06:07.145
My strategy was to keep it in my mouth

06:07.147 --> 06:10.448
and try and just build up
the saliva, build up the saliva.

06:10.450 --> 06:13.785
But it's just too much.
It's too much cinnamon.

06:13.787 --> 06:15.653
Maybe it would be possible

06:15.655 --> 06:18.690
with half that amount or 1/4 that amount,

06:18.692 --> 06:22.193
but a tablespoon full... you can't do it.

06:22.195 --> 06:23.494
All right.

06:23.496 --> 06:25.029
Tory is about to find out for sure,

06:25.031 --> 06:27.398
and he does have the slight advantage

06:27.400 --> 06:30.068
of seeing two failed strategies in action.

06:30.070 --> 06:32.136
Oh, look at that. Into the cheek.

06:32.138 --> 06:33.771
Chewing-tobacco style.

06:33.773 --> 06:35.673
He's doing good so far.

06:35.675 --> 06:37.108
He really is.

06:37.110 --> 06:40.078
Tory has squirreled
the cinnamon into his cheeks

06:40.080 --> 06:42.347
and is trying to work up
the saliva he needs

06:42.349 --> 06:44.982
to overcome its absorbent qualities.

06:44.984 --> 06:46.684
But can he go the distance?

06:46.686 --> 06:47.852
Still going strong.

06:47.854 --> 06:50.088
He's like at least a minute in.

06:50.090 --> 06:51.089
Mm-hmm.

06:51.091 --> 06:52.323
- It hurts?
- Mm.

06:52.325 --> 06:53.524
- It hurts a lot.
- Mm-hmm.

06:53.526 --> 06:55.693
Despite the discomfort, Tory keeps going.

06:55.695 --> 06:57.695
I think I got this one beat.

06:57.697 --> 06:59.063
But <i>you</i> shouldn't.

06:59.065 --> 07:01.933
This is definitely one to <i>not</i> try at home.

07:01.935 --> 07:03.868
Oh, my God.

07:03.870 --> 07:05.436
- You're swallowing it.
- Mm.

07:07.072 --> 07:08.206
Whoo!

07:08.208 --> 07:09.340
I did it.

07:09.342 --> 07:11.175
- Hey!
- Yes!

07:11.177 --> 07:12.210
Busted!

07:12.212 --> 07:14.312
So, it turns out this one is busted.

07:14.314 --> 07:17.982
You can eat a spoonful of
cinnamon without drinking water,

07:17.984 --> 07:20.318
but whatever you do,
do not try this at home.

07:20.320 --> 07:21.619
Seriously.

07:21.621 --> 07:23.554
Not only is it painful,
it is also very dangerous.

07:23.556 --> 07:26.424
In fact, hundreds of kids
have ended up in the hospital

07:26.426 --> 07:28.493
attempting to do what we just did.

07:28.495 --> 07:30.962
Not only that,
we had a doctor standing by.

07:30.964 --> 07:33.297
Plus, we had to get a medical examination

07:33.299 --> 07:34.999
before and after the experiment.

07:35.001 --> 07:37.034
Seriously, this is bad news.

07:37.036 --> 07:39.771
Looks like I win and lose
at the same time.

07:39.773 --> 07:41.406
Congratulations.

07:47.513 --> 07:50.615
"Dear MythBusters, who does
your blueprint drawings?"

07:50.617 --> 07:52.083
That's easy. Our own Eric Haven.

07:52.085 --> 07:53.718
He's one of our associate producers.

07:53.720 --> 07:54.919
All right. Next question.

07:54.921 --> 07:56.187
I think our viewers deserve

07:56.189 --> 07:57.822
a little more of an answer than that.

07:59.491 --> 08:01.426
Yep, not a week goes by

08:01.428 --> 08:03.261
when the mailbag
isn't filled with questions

08:03.263 --> 08:06.164
about this international man of mystery.

08:06.166 --> 08:08.733
How many years do you think
you've been doing pushups?

08:08.735 --> 08:10.868
I don't know. Are my pecs distracting you?

08:10.870 --> 08:13.204
Who is this bespectacled sex God

08:13.206 --> 08:15.740
with the impeccable penmanship, you ask?

08:17.177 --> 08:21.012
For answers, here's an exclusive
sneak peek behind the scenes.

08:21.014 --> 08:23.614
Eric Haven, say hello
to the "MythBusters" audience.

08:23.616 --> 08:24.749
Hello.

08:24.751 --> 08:26.651
Now, we used to do the drawings for this.

08:28.654 --> 08:30.788
How did you end up doing
all the blueprint drawings?

08:30.790 --> 08:32.356
Well, the executive producer knew

08:32.357 --> 08:33.857
that I was a comic book artist,

08:33.860 --> 08:35.693
so he thought that I should take a crack

08:35.695 --> 08:37.061
at these blueprint drawings.

08:37.063 --> 08:38.796
And the first one turned out pretty swell,

08:38.798 --> 08:40.298
so I've been doing them ever since.

08:41.601 --> 08:42.732
How many do you think you've done?

08:44.670 --> 08:46.938
Probably close to 500.

08:46.940 --> 08:49.006
What are some of the favorite
drawings you've done for the show?

08:49.008 --> 08:52.376
Well, I liked
the "flying guillotine" drawing.

08:52.378 --> 08:55.046
And the "battle of the sexes"
was fun, too.

08:55.048 --> 08:57.515
Both of them featured decapitated Torys.

08:57.517 --> 08:59.884
How does it feel to be
on this side of the camera?

08:59.886 --> 09:01.919
It feels very strange and unnatural.

09:03.723 --> 09:05.122
Well, why don't you sign that?

09:07.494 --> 09:09.794
Okay. My turn.

09:09.796 --> 09:11.963
"You get some great
high-speeds on the show."

09:11.965 --> 09:13.097
"What's your favorite,"

09:13.099 --> 09:14.899
"and have you ever missed the shot?"

09:14.901 --> 09:17.101
Uh, yeah. Does anybody remember
the cement truck?

09:18.670 --> 09:19.904
Hey, hey!

09:19.906 --> 09:21.939
All right! Whoo!

09:21.941 --> 09:24.642
<i>The</i> most famous explosion
in "MythBusters" history,

09:24.644 --> 09:26.811
and we don't have a high-speed shot of it

09:26.813 --> 09:28.079
from a technical glitch.

09:28.081 --> 09:29.380
Fire in the hole.

09:29.382 --> 09:32.617
Yeah, we had to slow down
the real-time footage.

09:35.854 --> 09:37.688
When you're shooting these events,

09:37.690 --> 09:39.891
they happen so quickly
that they're very unpredictable,

09:39.893 --> 09:41.025
and it's hard to catch them.

09:41.027 --> 09:42.260
Yeah, but what's your favorite?

09:42.262 --> 09:43.794
Oh, mine's definitely "car skip."

09:47.933 --> 09:50.034
I mean, seeing that yellow sports car

09:50.036 --> 09:53.271
flip end over end on the water,
it's like automotive ballet.

09:54.506 --> 09:56.908
Mine is similar to ballet.

09:56.910 --> 09:58.509
It's when Adam was on the treadmill...

09:58.511 --> 10:00.344
Ugh!

10:00.346 --> 10:01.746
and he landed on his face.

10:03.382 --> 10:05.783
Okay! I'm totally cool!

10:05.785 --> 10:07.785
I never get tired of watching that.

10:07.787 --> 10:12.423
Or what about
when Adam was fire walking?

10:12.425 --> 10:14.592
Aah!

10:14.594 --> 10:16.761
Or what about when he was
swinging the bat?

10:16.763 --> 10:17.862
Ah!

10:17.864 --> 10:20.231
Ah! Ah! Ah! Ah!

10:20.233 --> 10:23.434
Yeah, but no one can forget
when Adam got slapped by Jamie.

10:26.806 --> 10:28.706
Oh, my God!

10:28.708 --> 10:30.374
It's like
your whole head is rubber.

10:30.376 --> 10:32.343
So, basically
any time Adam gets hurt.

10:32.345 --> 10:34.178
Shots of Adam being abused...

10:34.180 --> 10:35.246
- and misused...
- Ohh!

10:35.248 --> 10:37.248
- are the most memorable.
- Aah!

10:37.250 --> 10:38.649
Can we move on
to something else now?

10:38.651 --> 10:41.152
Here we go. Cut.

10:41.154 --> 10:43.521
But the state-of-the-art
camera technology

10:43.523 --> 10:47.058
is used to capture
an array of incredible images.

10:47.060 --> 10:50.261
And aside from
the occasional missed moment,

10:50.263 --> 10:51.429
the team behind the camera

10:51.431 --> 10:54.799
always artfully catches
the split-second action

10:54.801 --> 10:56.801
for your viewing pleasure.

10:56.803 --> 10:59.036
That might be one of my favorite
high-speed shots we've ever gotten.

10:59.038 --> 11:00.304
That's gorgeous.

11:00.306 --> 11:03.207
Coming up on the mailbag special...

11:03.209 --> 11:04.809
Ooh, this could be a show in itself.

11:04.811 --> 11:06.811
a flash in the van.

11:06.813 --> 11:08.879
Is Jamie man or mustache?

11:08.881 --> 11:10.615
And it's tool time.

11:16.022 --> 11:18.089
Do not try what
you're about to see at home.

11:18.091 --> 11:19.557
We're what you call experts.

11:19.559 --> 11:20.725
Ow!

11:27.133 --> 11:28.366
â™ª Come on

11:28.368 --> 11:29.734
Kari, Grant and Tory

11:29.736 --> 11:31.703
are catching up on correspondence.

11:31.705 --> 11:33.038
Fire!

11:34.340 --> 11:36.374
They're answering
your queries...

11:36.376 --> 11:37.842
Definitely good to start with a bang.

11:37.844 --> 11:39.077
and questions...

11:39.079 --> 11:40.679
So, basically any time Adam gets hurt.

11:40.681 --> 11:43.782
and testing a mailbag of mini myths.

11:44.918 --> 11:46.651
So, what's next?

11:46.653 --> 11:49.387
"In the show, it usually takes
you guys about half an hour"

11:49.389 --> 11:51.256
"to test a myth from start to finish."

11:51.258 --> 11:53.992
"If you bust it early,
you then replicate the results."

11:53.994 --> 11:56.428
"But when you confirm a myth,
the story ends."

11:58.331 --> 12:00.065
Wow!

12:00.067 --> 12:01.333
Totally confirmed.

12:01.335 --> 12:03.735
"My question is, have you ever
confirmed a myth so early"

12:03.737 --> 12:06.571
"that you didn't have enough time
to tell the story?"

12:06.573 --> 12:08.406
Yeah, there have been some times
where this has happened.

12:08.408 --> 12:11.476
But then there was one story
that worked so well

12:11.478 --> 12:13.244
that we had to throw the whole thing out,

12:13.246 --> 12:15.680
which is a shame because it was
a pretty awesome explosion.

12:15.682 --> 12:17.349
So, why don't we show it now?

12:17.351 --> 12:20.085
The myth of the "vanishing van"

12:20.087 --> 12:23.955
was a classic case
of premature confirmation.

12:23.957 --> 12:27.058
The story lasted
for just one brief explosion

12:27.060 --> 12:29.928
that, until now,
has been sitting on the shelf.

12:29.930 --> 12:31.663
Grant, take it away.

12:32.933 --> 12:35.867
So, this guy was working in
a Russian chemical factory,

12:35.869 --> 12:38.003
and he left his van over the weekend.

12:38.005 --> 12:39.571
There was a chemical leak.

12:39.573 --> 12:42.040
The van became filled with
a mystery concoction

12:42.042 --> 12:43.274
of different gases...

12:43.276 --> 12:46.211
oxygen, hydrogen, propane,
methane, who knows.

12:46.213 --> 12:48.179
So, he comes out after the weekend

12:48.181 --> 12:50.348
to unlock his van with his key remote.

12:50.350 --> 12:52.083
Boop-boop! Bang!

12:52.085 --> 12:54.352
The van explodes.

12:54.354 --> 12:55.954
Now, we set up the test full scale,

12:55.956 --> 12:57.555
assuming that it wasn't gonna work.

12:57.557 --> 12:59.858
Which is exactly what
all the scientists we talked to

12:59.860 --> 13:01.960
said was gonna happen or...
not happen.

13:01.962 --> 13:03.828
Then...

13:03.830 --> 13:05.597
it worked perfectly the first time,

13:05.599 --> 13:06.798
so we didn't have any story to tell.

13:06.800 --> 13:08.033
So, the question

13:08.035 --> 13:09.868
the team was attempting to answer was,

13:09.870 --> 13:12.404
could a remote control ignite a van

13:12.406 --> 13:15.373
that had filled with flammable gas?

13:15.375 --> 13:17.575
Our research team said, "no way!"

13:17.577 --> 13:21.713
And so, step one was
to go for it in full scale.

13:21.715 --> 13:25.216
And now we seal it. No leaks.

13:25.218 --> 13:26.618
Expecting that to fail,

13:26.620 --> 13:29.721
the team would then get into
the science of stoichiometry

13:29.723 --> 13:33.024
and replicate the results
any way they could.

13:33.026 --> 13:36.261
Aw, yeah. We got some '70s van going now.

13:36.263 --> 13:37.862
At least, that was the plan.

13:37.864 --> 13:39.230
All right. To the bat cave.

13:39.232 --> 13:40.465
But with the van rigged

13:40.467 --> 13:43.501
and ready to fill with
a mystery gas cocktail,

13:43.503 --> 13:47.072
that plan went up in smoke... literally.

13:47.074 --> 13:49.374
All right.
You guys ready to start filling?

13:49.376 --> 13:50.442
I'm ready.

13:50.444 --> 13:52.677
3...2...1.

13:52.679 --> 13:53.878
Commence filling.

13:53.880 --> 13:56.047
All right. Time to start it.

13:56.049 --> 13:58.216
The chemical van begins to fill,

13:58.218 --> 14:00.552
but no one is expecting a big boom.

14:00.554 --> 14:02.687
So, the only tension is from bad acting.

14:02.689 --> 14:04.122
It's quiet out there.

14:04.124 --> 14:05.990
Almost <i>too</i> quiet.

14:05.992 --> 14:07.425
And as soon as the van is full

14:07.427 --> 14:10.495
with a weekend's worth of a slow gas leak,

14:10.497 --> 14:13.431
Grant, from a safe distance,
is ready to simulate

14:13.433 --> 14:16.167
the electronic signal of the key remote.

14:16.169 --> 14:19.270
But the team is not expecting
a detonation.

14:19.272 --> 14:21.739
3...2...1...

14:22.775 --> 14:25.076
- Aah!
- Aah! Aah!

14:25.078 --> 14:27.045
Oh, man!

14:27.047 --> 14:28.713
Stuff's still dropping!

14:28.715 --> 14:29.848
Oh, my gosh!

14:29.850 --> 14:33.952
That ladder went over 200 feet in the air!

14:33.954 --> 14:35.920
I think this is freaking confirmed!

14:35.922 --> 14:37.188
Let's go look at the carnage.

14:37.190 --> 14:38.690
- I want to check this out.
- Oh, my God!

14:38.692 --> 14:39.891
That's a lot of power.

14:41.460 --> 14:43.561
In 1/1000 of a second,

14:43.563 --> 14:46.498
the unexpected explosion
blew the roof off the van

14:46.500 --> 14:48.833
and sent debris far and wide,

14:48.835 --> 14:50.869
leaving the team
with an early confirmation

14:50.871 --> 14:54.272
and the smoldering wreckage of a story.

14:54.274 --> 14:56.241
We hit the ignition system,

14:56.243 --> 15:00.078
and then instantly there was
this huge, orange fire ball

15:00.080 --> 15:02.180
and the van was disintegrated.

15:02.182 --> 15:03.882
I mean, can you imagine coming out,

15:03.884 --> 15:05.550
hitting the remote key on your car,

15:05.552 --> 15:07.218
and it blowing up in front of you?

15:07.220 --> 15:10.388
We just saw that firsthand.
This one's confirmed.

15:10.390 --> 15:13.057
Yep. Confirmed.

15:13.059 --> 15:16.528
But one quick flash in the van
wasn't enough for a whole story.

15:16.530 --> 15:19.063
However, it did answer your question.

15:19.065 --> 15:20.498
So, what's next?

15:20.500 --> 15:23.535
"It seems that Jamie is
the ultimate straight man."

15:23.537 --> 15:24.903
Happy.

15:24.905 --> 15:26.171
"Is that an act,"

15:26.173 --> 15:28.006
"or does he really show
very little emotion?"

15:28.008 --> 15:29.841
Sad.

15:29.843 --> 15:31.876
I've known him for quite a long time,

15:31.878 --> 15:34.412
and I've never seen him get
too emotional about too much.

15:34.414 --> 15:36.281
I kind of like it in here. It's private.

15:36.283 --> 15:38.583
But he <i>does</i> get excited about things.

15:38.585 --> 15:40.351
Bye-bye!

15:40.353 --> 15:42.687
When in doubt, C-4.

15:43.823 --> 15:45.423
Like when they were working
on the jet pack,

15:45.425 --> 15:47.192
the first time they fired it up.

15:47.194 --> 15:48.593
When the mustache waves up,

15:48.595 --> 15:51.663
you can actually see kind of
a smile happening under there.

15:51.665 --> 15:54.065
So, it does happen occasionally.

15:54.067 --> 15:56.434
I've never seen Jamie so happy in my life.

15:56.436 --> 15:59.270
So, not giggling like a school
girl or anything like that.

15:59.272 --> 16:00.872
Jamie wants big boom.

16:00.874 --> 16:02.106
No, not usually.

16:02.108 --> 16:03.942
Like a big, buff, bald school girl

16:03.944 --> 16:05.710
with a beret and a mustache?

16:05.712 --> 16:07.745
- Okay, now I'm disturbed.
- Me too.

16:07.747 --> 16:09.314
I feel kind of sexy.

16:09.316 --> 16:10.782
With Jamie, what you see is what you get...

16:10.784 --> 16:14.586
part walrus, part robot, mostly mustache.

16:14.588 --> 16:17.121
He's just a regular, beret-wearing genius,

16:17.123 --> 16:19.891
who, while keeping
his emotions under control,

16:19.893 --> 16:21.893
likes to wear high heels.

16:21.895 --> 16:23.995
It's just another day on the job.

16:23.997 --> 16:25.330
So, this fan writes in...

16:25.332 --> 16:27.298
ooh, this could be a show in itself.

16:27.300 --> 16:30.902
"What is your favorite tool
in the shop and why?"

16:30.904 --> 16:32.604
Well, why don't we split up
and do a little show-and-tell?

16:35.040 --> 16:38.243
Building, rigging, replicating,

16:38.245 --> 16:40.745
modeling, construction, and deconstruction

16:40.747 --> 16:44.182
are in some way part
of every "MythBusters" story.

16:44.184 --> 16:48.253
And to do it, the team uses
a whole heap of cool tools.

16:51.725 --> 16:53.258
Aw.

16:53.260 --> 16:55.460
My favorite tool in the shop...
besides Tory...

16:55.462 --> 16:57.595
Ohh!

16:57.597 --> 16:59.330
is the plasma cutter.

16:59.332 --> 17:02.200
It instantly liquifies metal.

17:02.202 --> 17:05.670
It basically uses compressed air
and an electric arc

17:05.672 --> 17:08.071
to cut out any shape you need.

17:09.974 --> 17:12.010
So, what's <i>my</i> favorite tool in our shop?

17:12.012 --> 17:13.211
Well, it's our forklift.

17:14.880 --> 17:17.548
Our forklift is a little bit different.

17:17.550 --> 17:19.617
See, it's got these four omni wheels

17:19.618 --> 17:21.919
that let it do all kinds of crazy moves,

17:21.921 --> 17:24.088
like spin in a circle...

17:24.089 --> 17:25.857
or track side-to-side.

17:25.858 --> 17:28.893
In fact, it can do
all these moves at once,

17:28.895 --> 17:31.162
simultaneously.

17:35.035 --> 17:38.536
What I have here is
a 14-inch, 5-horsepower,

17:38.538 --> 17:41.372
gasoline-powered cut-off saw.

17:43.810 --> 17:46.044
This thing's capable
of cutting through concrete,

17:46.046 --> 17:48.112
rock, even steel!

17:51.083 --> 17:54.118
In fact, my favorite time
I used this on the show was

17:54.120 --> 17:55.620
when we cut a car in half!

17:56.889 --> 17:59.157
This tool gets the job done!

18:01.093 --> 18:03.127
And that sums up
the team's tool preferences...

18:03.129 --> 18:05.863
cool, hot cutting...

18:05.865 --> 18:07.098
wheely versatility...

18:07.100 --> 18:09.967
and testosterone-fueled demolition.

18:09.969 --> 18:12.670
Next up, we're gonna blow up
this washing machine with C-4.

18:12.672 --> 18:15.273
We're gonna take this one to the cleaners.

